eliud_pkg_text-htmlWithPlatformMediums.html:
Follow the below steps to create your own app...

Step 1: Go to Apps and press the '+' button

Step 2: Select a unique name

Accept the new name, click 'v' and wait for the app to be created.

Step 3: Accept the Policies (which don't exist)


Step 4: Switch to "edit mode" by clicking the edit button


Plenty of buttons appear. These buttons allow you to update the contents of your app.

Step 5: Now press the "wizard button"

Step 6: Select a wizard, e.g. fader and press 'go', then wait...

Step 7: Open left drawer and select "Fader"

Observe the results of the wizard: the fader:

Step 8: Press the styles button to change style

Step 9: Follow on screen instructions to select select, copy or update a (copy) of an instance of style


Below a few screenshots of the same fader page with different style:

Eliud style


Juuwle style


Minkey style


Further steps

Congratulations, you've created your first app, created a fader page and selected a style for your app.

What's next?

You could play with a few more wizards for example. Or ... You might have noticed the "editor mode" has made a few buttons available. You could play with these buttons, they should be self-explanatory. If you need more detailed explain, see Tech

At launch of Minkey July 2022, 2 example websites/apps were made available: Juuwle and Eliud. These are available from "Apps". As mentioned, apps created on Minkey can also be made available as stand-alone apps. To illustrate, we have made these 2 example apps also available as juuwle.com and eliud.io.

Welcome to Minkey

Minkey is a platform which allows you to create apps and websites.

Minkey allows you to build your website and/or app online. You can present your products, your services, yourself, choose to include a social media feed, add a chat or perhaps add your online store. You can select a style for your app and configure it with your preferred colours, backgrounds, logo(s), etc.  Share the app with your friends and build a community. If you like what you see on Minkey, you can eventually choose to port your app / website as a stand-alone app, outside and without any reference to minkey.io

Minkey is available as Android app and as website minkey.io

The Apple app is being reviewed and will be available soon.

Windows, Linux, MacOS and Fuchsia apps are being considered.

By the way... Minkey was made with Minkey

1. Introduction

Minkey runs on iOS, Android and the web.

Minkey uses Google Firebase for backend processing, such as storrage. authentication, hosting and so on.

Minkey uses Eliud technology.

  • Eliud technology is open source technology. The documentation for eliud is being compiled to make the technology available as open source. ETA Januari 2023.
  • The technology allows to build apps and/or websites. Today, app content can include photo galleries, pages with videos and images (html), social media, chat with or between members, your shop / shopping cart, photo sliders, documents, and more. A complete list below.
  • Eliud is a layer on top of Flutter. Flutter is an open-source UI software development kit created by Google. Flutter allows to develop cross platform applications for iOS, Android and web as well as Linux, macOS, Windows and Google Fuchsia.
  • Eliud is to Flutter as Wordpress is to html: Wordpress and many other similar technologies allow people without knowledge of html to build websites. Flutter allows to build websites and apps, or even Windows, Linux, macOS and Google Fuchsia apps, with limited technical knowledge. However, Flutter requires programming skills and technical knowledge of building websites / apps. Eliud allows to do so without these skills/knowledge.
  • Eliud is pluggable technology, allowing developers to extend / add functionalities by means of plugins.
  • A website / app built with Eliud consist of its core Eliud package + one or more Eliud plugins. The app is constructed by configuring it. Configuration, images and videos are stored in Firebase database and Firebase storage.

Because Minkey uses Eliud technology, it means everything you make on the Minkey platform can also run as a stand-alone app and/or website, provided you install your own Firebase instance: The Minkey platform allows to extract your app configuration as json and download it as a blob. This json blob can then be used to be deployed on your own Google Firebase instance, deploy on your Google hosting and/or upload as Apple iOS and/or Android app. Et voila, you've got yourself your own app / website with minimum effort and investment. Obviously you can as well bypass using Minkey alltogether and start with an Eliud app directly. More information about all this below and obviously on eliud.io.

2 How?

2.1 The Eliud app

2.1.1 Navigation

First of all, an Eliud app consists of pages with drawers, an app bar and a bottom navigation bar.


Links to pages or dialogs are available from the appbar, the bottom navigation bar and from the drawers. The appbar has icons on the left and right to open the left and right drawer. When not logged on, the appbar typically has a sign in button. We say "typically" as this totally depends on the creator of the app chooses to configure these things. Also typically, the appbar has "context dependent icons" such as a chat icon, a cart icon, a message icon respectively indicating the existance of an unread entry in a chat, an unread message or items in a shopping cart. These icons can be placed everywhere, but typcially they're placed on the appbar.

The bottom navigation bar: Icons with references to pages of your app, typically the main sections of your app.


The left and right drawers also have menu items which open a page or a dialog. The left drawer typically displays the app logo and lists links to pages within the app. The right drawer typically is only accessible for people who have logged into the app and therefore this drawer typically contains the avatar of the member and a list actions of the member, for example a dialog that allows to maintain the member's account.

2.1.2 Pages, dialogs and components

Pages and dialogs consist of 1 or more components. For example:


In the above example page, here the "Apps" page of the Minkey app itself, we have 3 components: a Fader, a Divider and a Playstore.

2.1.3 Privileges / access level

You might want to allow some bits to be accessible by some specific members only for example. For this, Eliud uses a concept of "privilege" to allow to secure certain parts of your app. This privilege can be: No Privilege, Level 1, Level 2 or Owner. A page and its components have a specific privilege. 

A person opening your app has a specific access level with corresponding access:

Access level Characteristics of person
 Access to pages, dialogs and components and images from components with privilege
Public
 Person has not subscribed, i.e. not logged onto the app. No Privilege
Subscribed
 Person has subscribed and logged onto the app but has not been given any access level No Privilege
Level 1 Person has subscred and logged onto the app and has given access level 1 Level 1
Level 2 Person has subscred and logged onto the app and has given access level 2
 Level 2
Owner Person has logged onto the app and is the owner Owner
Blocked Person has logged onto the app but has been blocked by the owner No privilege

Notes:

  • It should go without saying, but authentication and authorization is not managed by the app, but managed by GCP. Authentication is the process of verifying who a user is, while authorization is the process of verifying what they have access to. 
  • Blocked members can see what public can see. The app will behave in some different ways to indicate to the person that he is blocked. However, this limitation is only indicative. All the person has to do is logoff and use the app anonymously to access public info, hence no extra limitation for blocked users vs public users. If you want to limit access to data, this data needs to be specified as level 1, 2 or owner.

2.2 Editor mode

As owner of your app, you (and only you) can switch to editor mode: If you are the owner of the current app, there will be be an editor toggle mode button available at the bottom of the window.


When you press the editor toggle mode button, a number of buttons will appear. These buttons allow you to construct / adjust your app. By the way, sometimes these editor buttons could be overlapping other buttons or functionality of your app. Because of this, you can move these buttons around.


StyleAllows to change the style of your app, see 2.2.1 Style
WizardAllows to add functionality to your app by means of a wizard, see 2.2.2 Wizard
AppAllows to update the app, see 2.2.3 App
PageAllows to update the page, see 2.2.4 Page
AppBarAllows to update the app bar, see 2.2.5 AppBar
Bottom NavAllows to update the bottom navigation menu, see 2.2.6 Bottom Nav
Component Editor: FaderAllows to update the component which is an editor specific to that component, here the Fader, see 2.2.8 Component Editor
Component Editor: DividerAllows to update the component which is an editor specific to that component, here the Divider, see 2.2.8 Component Editor
Component Editor: PlaystoreAllows to update the component which is an editor specific to that component, here the Playstore, see 2.2.8 Component Editor


DrawerAllows to change the style of your drawer, see 2.2.7 Drawer

2.2.1 Style

The style dialog allows the app creator to use any of the pre-defined styles, to copy, to name it, and to select it as the default style.


Minkey uses an API that can be implemented by plugins. A default style is provided which serves as a minimum default implementation. A "nicer" implementation has been made available by the plugin "eliud_stl_mona". Use the on screen instructions to copy, configure and select the style for your app. Recommended is that you copy one of the predefined styles into your own style and configure. Don't forget to make it the active style.

2.2.2 Wizard

An app consists of one or more pages. Pages can be created through the various editors, more on that later. However, to simplify things, most plugins come with wizards to simplify the creation of the components it provides and to setup one or more pages for it.

Click on the wizard button opens the wizard page.


On this wizard page, you can select a package / plugin. After selecting a package, the wizards available in that package are then listed. Click on one of these wizards to configure it and run it. A wizard typically generates 1 or more pages. Also typically, a wizard allows you to indicate from which menu to access these pages, i.e. from the left drawer, right drawer, bottom navigation bar or appbar. Or, you can choose to generate one or more pages and make it available to be referred to from within another page / component.

A wizard simplifies the introduction of functionality to your app. Everything you can do with a wizard can also be done manually through multiple steps by means of the component editor. More on the component editor below.

The list of wizards depends on the packages that are available. Upgrades of packages might introduce new wizards. The current wizards are the below:

2.2.3 App editor

Press the App editor button opens the app dialog. 


This dialog can be used to configure the following:

2.2.3.1 General


General settings allow to change the web URL, the title, the description and the email address of your app.

The flag "Auto privilege level 1 for new members" allows the owner of the app to indicate that new members of that app should automatically get level 1 privilege. Otherwise there's practically no difference in privilege between a member and a non member. So the app owner might want to give some extra privileges to people subscribing as member. More on privileges later.

The flag "Featured" allows to present your app in Minkey's play store.

2.2.3.2 Logo

Allows to change the logo of your app

2.2.3.3 Profile photo for member with no photo

Allows to set the avatar for people with no photo

2.2.3.4 Profile photo for member with no photo

2.2.8 Component editor

The component editor is specific to the component. Below the component editor for the component "html". This editor allows you to update the html, as html or visually. The interface allows to upload images, etc. This component editor was used to update this page you are looking at right now.
